vectorData.altText: 4. Which skeletal muscle(s) of the abdominal wall is (are), in part, aponeurotic? Choose all that apply.
That's right!  The external oblique, internal oblique and transversus abdominis are the three flat muscle which become aponeurotic as they approach anterior aspect of abdominal wall.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

The anterolateral abdominal wall includes three broad flat muscles arranged in layers.  These flat muscles begin with posterior attachments to ribs, vertebrae and pelvis, where they are fleshy and contractile. 
As they approach the anterior aspect of the abdominal wall, they become aponeurotic     , non-contractile sheets that interlace in the midline, forming the linea alba     .
L. “white line”; it runs vertically in the midline from the xiphoid process to the pubis
a sheet of pearly-white fibrous tissue that takes the place of a tendon in sheet-like muscles having a wide area of attachment
On either side of the linea alba, a single vertical muscle, the rectus abdominis completes the abdominal wall anteriorly.
The rectus abdominis is enclosed in the rectus sheath, which is formed by the aponeuroses of the three flat muscles, as they pass anterior and posterior to the rectus abdominis.
